import java.sql.*;   // For Connection class, Statement etc., we need these classes from this package only (standard libraries). They're part of JDBC API which is included in Java SDK by default when you download and install the JDK or any other programming language environment for development purpose like IntelliJ IDEA.
import org.hibernate.*;  // For Session, Hibernate object etc., we need these classes from this package only (standard libraries). They're part of 'Hibernate ORM'. We are not using Spring here as per your requirement to avoid use spring framework components and dependencies in our code like session factory or transaction manager.
import java.util.*;  // For List, Set etc., we need these classes from this package only (standard libraries). They're part of Java Collections API which is included by default when you download the JDK as well. We are not using Spring here either due to mentioned constraints above. It may be considered overkill if our goal was just simple program, but it will definitely help in understanding how such a setup can work out for this task!